english:
  title: A Petition to Be Relieved of Office and Granted Time to Complete the Systematic Arrangement of the Book of Rites
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In years past, my teacher Han-san Yi Saek once said to me: "The Six Classics were all consumed by fire in the Qin dynasty, and the Book of Rites suffered the greatest loss. Han scholars gathered the scattered remnants from the ashes and recorded them in the order they were found, leaving the text in disarray without proper sequence. Only Master Cheng and Master Zhu organized the Great Learning into proper order, yet the rest remains unfinished. I have long wished to classify and arrange the material into a separate work, but have not yet accomplished it. I hope you will endeavor to complete this task."

    I received his instruction and have repeatedly attempted to arrange and organize the text, yet official duties have prevented me from fulfilling this obligation. During the previous reign, I fell into disgrace and exile. Through the compassionate grace of the Retired King, I was spared and allowed to dwell in peace in my native place. From the spring of the year Sinmi to the autumn of the year Imsin—some ten months—I finally had the opportunity to study this classic deeply. Following the arrangement of the text, I produced a draft. Yet because the original work contains such vast and complex material, it proved impossible to transcribe it completely. I have merely noted the opening and closing characters of each section, indicating where passages had been placed before and where they should rightfully be arranged now, occasionally adding my own interpretive notes below.

    My intention was to complete the original text first, then arrange the interpretations of Master Chen, and finally append my own understanding to form a complete work. But how could such a task be accomplished by one man's effort in mere months? Thus at that time I could not finish the manuscript, hoping only to complete it with my remaining years.

    At the founding of this dynasty, I was called to service. When Your Majesty ascended the throne, though I had rendered no merit, I was undeservedly placed among the meritorious ministers, elevated to the position of Prime Minister, and twice honored with the covenant. My gratitude knows no bounds; even if my body were ground to powder, it could not repay such kindness.

    Yet I must consider: my constitution has always been frail and prone to illness, and now these afflictions grow ever more severe. My limbs grow weary, my head and eyes spin with dizziness, my mind grows clouded and forgetful, my ears are deaf and heavy with age, making it difficult to fulfill my duties. Diviners have said that from the year Eulyu through the years Jeonghai and Munja, calamitous fortune awaits me—barely survivable, they claim. Though such words may not merit credence, judging from my many illnesses, I can well imagine that my years are numbered.

    More than ten years have passed since I began this compilation, yet it remains unfinished. I fear that any day now, my ailments may overcome me, and as the sun sets in the west, I may suddenly depart this flourishing age, leaving my teacher's final wish unfulfilled in the grave. Is this not a cause for deep sorrow?

    Moreover, I possess only shallow knowledge and have long served in court without rendering the slightest benefit. Should my position be relieved and my worldly duties removed, allowing me to devote myself wholly to completing this work, then though my presumption and rashness cannot escape censure, surely the later generation of scholars would gain some benefit. I humbly beseech Your Majesty to take pity on this aging and ailing servant, to understand my earnest wishes, and to grant me leave from office. Allow me to rest in quiet retirement, and during intervals from taking medicine, to gather my remaining strength and complete this task. Command the appropriate officials to provide paper and scribes to prepare the final manuscript, and have it printed and distributed. Though my work may be of little worth, surely the coming generation of scholars will be inspired by it, will expound the classics and illuminate them, and will thereby glorify Your Majesty's age of literary culture.

    I cannot contain my fervent though humble desire. I present this with deepest reverence and awe.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Han-san Yi Saek (1328-1396) was a renowned Goryeo scholar and Kwon Geun's most important teacher.
  - key: ''
    value: The Six Classics refer to the ritual texts, music, odes, history, spring and autumn annals, and the changes—the foundational texts of Chinese learning.
  - key: ''
    value: Master Cheng refers to Cheng Yi and Master Zhu to Zhu Xi, the great Neo-Confucian philosophers whose interpretations of classical texts became standard.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Retired King' refers to the father of the reigning monarch, a common arrangement in early Joseon governance.
  - key: ''
    value: The years mentioned (Eulyu, Jeonghai, Munja) refer to specific years in the sexagenary cycle, used in traditional East Asian calendrical systems.
